A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama's Re-election
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Centre considers it a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of American governments enacted new laws from 2009 on making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
The new electoral laws require electors to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day, and remove the right of citizens with judicial records to vote.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the law of Indiana.
The republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other States.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have universal identity cards such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such identification.
However, it often costs more than $100 to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
Twenty-five per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 per cent of citizens over the age of 65 and 20 per cent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
Much more.
Students, who are considered to vote more for democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the republican side to use the cards issued by those clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favour the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators sponsored laws abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states in 2011.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to electors wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of approximately 10 million citizens.
However, measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17 per cent in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the advance voting period.
For example, at the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of the electors who voted in advance were African Americans, while they represented only 13% of the state's voters.
The same was true of the Hispanics.
They represented only 11 per cent of the voters, but 24 per cent of the citizens who voted in advance.
In return, white voters who made up 76 per cent of the voters represented only 46 per cent of the electors voting in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetos of the Democratic Governors.
The US Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of photo identification cards.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that were passed and see it as an obvious objective to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that the states that adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Screening for prostate cancer: take the test or not?
Indeed, the APS test would sometimes have erroneous results, with false negative results or false positives, which would lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This is why men who are already reluctant to take screening tests are even more reluctant to do so.
Take the test or not?
We asked for the advice of two specialists.
In studies in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another study, the European one, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had been screened and those who had not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that you are 30-40% more likely to have metastases if you are not detected.
So I recommend the test from the age of 50, or from the age of 40, if we have a direct relative who has had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American origin are also at greater risk.
The key is to make the right decision once we've detected cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are painless.
There is a real need to make the patient understand the level of risk of cancer, by providing them with the possible options, by not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect long-term life, and by opting instead, in these cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We're going to suggest active surveillance and if the disease progresses, we're going to offer them treatment.
