The Higgs boson shelled
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole emotion, last summer, and for cause.
It is indeed believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behaviour of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that this is the Higgs.
We know without a doubt that we are holding an authentic new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data released this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely certain.
Let us assume that this is the Higgs, since the chances of error seem slim, and let's see what this is all about.
There is, in this world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break that rule - and don't try too hard, you're gonna hurt yourself.
But even if particle physics is a strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly in some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens named fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least, not for that principle, which means they can actually be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons then divide into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, moreover) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not deal with here, and the "particles of force," by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the boson of Higgs would be somehow related.
These bosons, as we must point out here, are not all as exotic as we might think.
In fact, if you can read this column, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light," which is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "interferes" with the electromagnetic field in this particular place, a bit like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" arises an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the bosons "force carriers."
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
However, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, a little as if it were a frozen pond whose only very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km of circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between Higgs and mass.
Not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on to itself on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, yours) do not.
Now, what can "bring" all this research, Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, it is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between MS observations and predictions.
There are also many who would like to be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and close some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge deficiencies, proposing no explanation for gravity (oups!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oups!).
But we haven't found such discrepancies at CERN so far.
Impact
The implications of this research in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. Tout-le-Monde are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work would trigger.
They could see scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - initially saw the laser as a "lab gadget."
Imagine...
And then the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his optical work.
This sensor, although not at all its original intention, now serves as the "eye" for all digital cameras in the world, and has earned it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, we never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die...; Le Devoir
With its Commission to die in dignity, Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is about to resume as a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this crucial area.
Le Devoir tried to look closer.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his Montérégie apartment.
The prostate cancer that swallowed him had given him a two-year respite.
"They gave me five years to live, I made seven years," he said, half-fig, half-grape, lying in bed at Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care House in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its job: a huge weakness that prevents it from going alone to the toilet, and even eating alone.
Attracted to an appetizing lunch, he agreed to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he can even smile, speaks to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicine, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is for me to be cured of diarrhea, which is humiliating," he confides.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In our life, we learn that a man is peeing on his feet," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois.
Regaining to the child's stage, for some people, is unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the ability of the person to accept regression," he says.
For, in the opinion of many palliative care workers, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients entering the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides "curative" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "conscious and stifled."
But the disease made me discover my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't have any more wishes in life," she says, before she accepts a mask to help her breathe.
Nevertheless, in the coming days, she is awaiting a final visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, with a group of volunteers, body care and food assistance are provided.
It is palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It's very little when you know you all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues under the best possible conditions, says Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the home's doctors.
Whether it's physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When dying, brandy or Pepsi will be accepted for oral care, depending on the request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died during the night.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the deceased's feet.
"We help loved ones as well as patients," says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow each other but do not resemble each other.
Alongside an old 93-year-old man who savors his last family assembly in the courtyard, well stocked in his pillows while being tricked in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after having tried everything to survive.
"For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois come from their home, 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of his or her life, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And many organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Société de soins palliatives à domicile du Grand Montréal, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that has led several palliative care physicians to fear the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health care system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in an emergency, in great pain, without the necessary steps being taken to relieve her.
I'm afraid patients only ask to die because they don't get the proper care.
And at the same time, many oncologists are struggling with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard's expectations of survival were already minimal when she gave up hard chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping the treatment, she told me that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she told me.
Yet she told me I was finished!
Not all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not having met their request after they were relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, Director of Palliative Care at the Société de soins palliatives à domicile du Grand Montréal, 8% of patients are refractory to pain treatments.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which amounts to sleeping until the patient's death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me," it means "I want to be relieved."
