With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
The opposite is true of current exchange rates, based on central banks, identified transactions and processing costs between stakeholders.
Moreover, as often in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, which is made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows peer-to-peer file exchange.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded through 15,000 computers on the network.
A small thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin price, after reaching a peak of $30 (€23) in June 2011, dropped to $2, five months later, before returning today around $10 (prices are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to world trade in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies."
Bitcoin stands out from other types of virtual currency such as "credits," used to advance in a video game that you win by playing or can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
But each time, a central authority controls and processes exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are both account book depositories, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses in the way of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double key encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file also make it possible to ensure that the bitcoins exchanged exist in the public accounts book, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers, whose winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a file hash phase, that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter, single digital fingerprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "chopping" the whole.
The aim is to find the number that gives a particular impression (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right number.
The transaction is then indestructively linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to defraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other one remains orphan because the two have different prints.
The computer that solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this award is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, which leaves some margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also noted with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Web sites providing services for Bitcoin were attacked and bitcoins in stolen deposits.
"The fault used does not concern the protocol itself," says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this flaw.
Weighing actors like Wikipedia refuse gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the account book and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "giant balances" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, believes very much in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a mobile payment without contact, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus return cheaper.
The bearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement in merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they need to do is communicate an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who assures thousands of users.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin to take over, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, if this currency is successful.
We left Afghanistan.
And then what?
French troops have left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Suo).
NATO and the Americans are expected to follow in late 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to take over its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting anything from us.
It is the Afghan peasants that we have punished by treating them as terrorists.
And ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the maimed.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former refugee leaders in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse the foreign armed presence, as in Soviet times.
They want to defend their ancient and archaic traditions, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistani, Arab, Uzbek, Tajik.
Tolerable, sometimes assisted by local insurgents, they will no longer be helped when the Westerners become more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the Nijrab base, which I observed from the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was in order.
The convoys of trucks and armoured vehicles reached Kabul without being attacked, overflown by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban outburst into Kabul by the end of 2014.
The circumstances have changed since their irresistible progress from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country on fire and bloodshed as a result of the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country was then seen as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of those peasants who have been overtaken by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved today.
Former Mujahedin, Afghan government and current Taliban are joining in the desire to keep women in a lower position.
The main leaders of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into businessmen, grabbing government land to sell it to refugees returning from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge US subcontracting contracts.
They have disregarded themselves; most of them have not fought themselves.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have been able to take advantage of American largesse: the flight of capital is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They met the modern world during their exils in Iran or Pakistan, they appreciated the benefits.
Approximately 65 per cent of the population is under the age of 25; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, one fifth of the total population.
In cities, government schools are full of girls and boys alike.
Work will have to be provided to these young people who will no longer want to return to the obscurantism of the old parties or to the corruption of certain leaders.
All, including the armed opponents, are fond of mobile phones; television, and its Turkish soap operas, which present a modern world, are followed everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities who will order it be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already concerned with rebuilding provincial militias, which will escape central government.
Afghanistan, a country of mountains, with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from a degree of decentralization, similar to Western nations, but the United States wanted to transform it into a centralized state with strong presidential power, abolishing the post of Prime Minister that had existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want any foreign controls, particularly during the elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and before.
No industry has been re-established, no dams are in operation, no major irrigation systems are being repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except fruit and vegetables.
Priority is left to private initiative.
In a country ruined by 30 years of war, government control over infrastructure would have been necessary.
There was a widespread rumour that Afghanistan possessed immense mineral wealth.
This only added to the feeling that Westerners were only there to seize it.
Without energy to process iron or copper ore on site, or transportation to export it across the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already almost left Mes Aynak's copper mine, allowing international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to search the huge Buddhist site and remain the province's largest employers.
Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports are heavily dependent, will also need one day to restore normal relations.
The departure of the French fighting troops was completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aids: lycée de filles, de garçons, département de français à l'université, Institut français, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support to the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win the hearts and minds" and to carry out the impossible task of matching aids and offensive actions, a "civil-military actions" department of the Ministry of Defence (Cimic), abolished in 2012, has carried out, and had carried out by a small French NGO, numerous works of collective interest and agricultural rehabilitation actions in dozens of mountain villages.
This work, which was greeted with local labour, was able to help contain the insurgency: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increased cropland.
What will we leave as a souvenir, after two billion euros in military spending?
A much smaller budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, which are very harsh in these valleys, often above 2,000 metres above sea level.
The Embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa Province.
In order to free themselves from the insurgency led by foreign groups, which the farmers told me they wanted, small, well-controlled civil aid should be maintained for them, which directly affects them.
A Constitution with Forceps in Egypt
This is another poker shot by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its vantage point.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State gave this House two more months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text for almost two years, several times amended which undermines institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the gap in the country.
For his opponents, the President persevered in his "autocratic delusion," continuing to "betray his word" and "trampling on the law."
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time which obliges the Brothers to give up their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote favourably, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
All the more so since this use of a hasty vote is the ultimatum of the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text or I retain full powers," which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It was in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, overwhelmingly Islamist, voted for the text yesterday.
Most Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slapped the door, believing that they had not been able to put forward their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities or civil society had done the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, replacement members, were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it was most often unanimously that the articles were voted on.
Commentators also amused themselves by the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the constituent's pendulum was not well settled.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
In the end, article 2 remains the same as that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia law are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the "establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace" principles "with" rules, "which would have allowed for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a sign of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," replied the Liberals, who only saw it as a communication blow.
For according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
These include article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular in verifying the conformity of laws with sharia law.
According to Egypt's expert Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the beginnings of a theocracy. "
The Liberals' fears are also fuelled by the fact that the next president of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the time being, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil register.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema but academics, for some trained in the French system "tempered Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he recognizes "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
Reference is made to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question may arise in the future as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to rule on it. "
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another contentious issue is the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as called for by human rights associations.
They also express their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including the press.
In addition, there is no longer any article that reflects the protection of women, Human Rights Watch's Heba Morayef points out.
In her view, the only positive point was the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian President was scheduled to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will parade them on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has chosen five major reasons to visit Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
A must-see rendez-vous: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that whoever penetrates these "baptismal funds" will be touched by the divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
It is in this particular place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers walk through the Rue de la Souffrance or the Way of the Cross (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This road begins near the Antonia fortress (the Praetory), where the trial was held, and then leads by the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, and then to that of the Stone of the Onction and the Tomb.
Here lies the Christian centre of the world, a symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to the Christian legend, the Monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified was grown.
Jerusalem also houses the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations, which is the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave there small words with prayers that are then answered.
Travel high
Visit the ruins of the Massada fortress, former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineers can go by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1 600 and 2 040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont, which welcomes many tourists during the winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
The old beliefs are that heathen gods once lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country houses nearly 300 museums.
It was impossible to visit all of them during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First of all: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judea Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
Also to be seen: Tel Aviv Art Museum.
The paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso are exhibited.
In Acre, the Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths made up of mouldings of the visitors and the watchmen of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Yad Vashem Holocaust Museum or Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars sparkle.
You then hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and welfare
Israel's three major resorts are on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each offers swimming pools, water parks, delphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, because the temperature of the water does not drop below 21 ° while that of the air can reach 23 °.
The Dead Sea is even hotter and you can swim all year round.
By the way, this is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point of the Earth, 417 m below sea level.
Azure-coloured water contains brine and very easily retains swimmers, even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are of surreal beauty.
We come here to treat with salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to just relax.
Discover the secrets of Antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the edge of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris that connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists particularly enjoy walking in the narrow alleys that bear the name of the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to take pictures of all Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre, "conquering" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, notably Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you leave for Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, because they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
With regard to urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost an underground funicular.
The journey to all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1: 30.
In Israel, Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cease to operate.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafés, restaurants and hotels only serve kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scaleless fish and dishes made of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes made from lamb and beef, soups and desserts made from coconut milk, but also hummus, traditional Jewish paste, various sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafel, fruit and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are a lot of well-fed cats who walk the haughty air.
They can be seen sleeping at night on the rooftops of parked cars.
These felins love passing places and do not refuse to be enjoyed.
Car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Rent a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
Admission to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mostly people coming to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who language has, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are polemics about what the law on compulsory language testing will give, fraudsters selling "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families at home.
Since 1 December, a law had entered into force stipulating that every migrant worker would have to pass an examination in Russian.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, with time, promises the Federal Migration Service, the tests will become compulsory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also of the history of Russia and the foundations of law.
It will be necessary to validate his knowledge of the Russian language in order to obtain and renew his work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian is an official language are exempt.
Persons who obtained educational certificates or diplomas before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not covered by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the Peoples' Friendship University, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions in Russia.
Immigrants will be able to take examinations in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders have already asked the question in the press many times: what will it give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, the representatives of the migration service respond, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery to work."
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, says the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problems of foreign workers at 90%.
The problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "journey" to an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellow men will torment themselves for months without food and without paper and will have to commute between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive numerous complaints from our migrants.
"At home, they are promised something, and when they arrive, they are cheated, they take their passports, and they do not receive the salary," confirms the Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the work of the Migration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't argue with me, police officer!
However, many Central Asian nationals who wish to come to Russia to earn money confide that they not only do not know the language of the country to which they wish to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is of course not their fault, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even fair primary education.
Their families don't even have enough food to feed their children, not to mention dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they confide.
"You feel diminished and weakened."
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
The examinations will be intended only for migrants with legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal review or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 miles rubles.
And then we can get a fake recording quickly for just 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They are asking us 100, 200 rubles for cigarettes and tea," said journalists Umed Khouchkadamov, a national of Tajikistan.
"Make it quick, don't lash and buy yourself a beautiful piece of art."
On the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that the registration documents of migrants were not the only ones to be false.
Several false certificates of language examinations have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
The forged papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners had nothing to do with them: each migrant who hoped to make it easier to take the examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The representatives of the government and human rights defenders agree that the short-term objective is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "pieces of paper."
The authorities may give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the examination on the first occasion the time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve active communication with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian weapons carriers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents, whether it be the shooting at weddings or the killing organized by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
The police want to ban the use of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a licence to carry a weapon from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee for Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the Arms Act would be introduced into the State Duma shortly.
Not everyone is happy to see that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw."
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demanded to abandon "this senseless hardening."
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, said the Russian service Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services, while 1,168 thousand crimes were registered in the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that strengthening civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from accessing the black market.
According to them, any weapon can be found in Moscow today for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior states that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black arms market is provided through several channels.
There are five main channels, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served 10 years in the Department of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot from a site taking orders for weapons
The first is the "military trace," that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians," Baranets explains.
The second type of black market weapons is those stolen from law enforcement agencies by criminals.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
The illegal pistols go for sale from the military warehouses.
Many of these have often been exploded.
"Certified versions indicate that some fires were deliberately triggered to conceal the deficit," explains the former member.
For Baranets, weapons manufacturers have something to do with it.
"We see private arms factories that do not compete with competition on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow," says an expert.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
A large proportion of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia has been formed and organizes the supply," adds the former military officer.
Where did the guns come from?
Experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, researchers explain, come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "because of employees whose work is related to weapons," the report explains.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from "clandestine searches."
A salesman and consultant from an arms store who asked to remain anonymous assures that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, the sellers will pick up the new goods from the military warehouses.
The person buys through a sign a unit, such as a TT pistol.
We deliver it to him by passing the merchandise through a fence.
"He transports it to the city and sells it for 900 €by the unit with two chargers," he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all the cases, so, when crimes are about to be solved, they make a purchase of control from illegal arms dealers," the seller adds.
"Like in a deluxe shop"
The seller and buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I looked at websites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered to come to Begovaya station where someone would take me to a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun was given to me on the spot.
Victor Baranets as a military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the salesman. I know someone, but I don't trust him.
There are sellers on the markets, but there is also a need to come and say, for example, "From such a person, who asked me to report that his daughter has lost a tooth."
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of someone I trust.
He only delivers them to me because he knows I won't give them to me.
The new kids are looking for guns in different ways.
Former soldier Victor Baranets tried himself as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, according to him, have not changed.
We gave him a photo album in which there was "everything we want."
"I thought I was in a deluxe shop," the soldier remembers.
There is no secret for the buyer, Baranets explains, we can try everything.
As a potential customer, I'm not just buying, we're going with the salesman in the forest and setting up a target.
"They let me shoot, and when I'm convinced that the gun is working well, we start negotiating," says the expert.
A shop from her couch
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where you can buy weapons "for different uses."
To do this, we don't need any documents and no one to meet.
"It's enough to have a specific amount of money," they write in advertising on the website "Buy a gun or a combat machine gun."
