"For the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain"
Recently, fans of new technologies have become accustomed to perceiving augmented reality through special glasses.
Initially, Google unveiled its current model this summer at its annual conference and in November it was reported that Microsoft had applied for the patent.
However, it appears from the interview with the director of the interactive 3D technology group of the Microsoft Cambridge laboratory, Shahram Izadi, that for scientists of this company, glasses are already of ancient history.
They are tempted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands, by the creation of open virtual spaces.
- Could you tell us in a few words what your research group is doing?
- We are working on the interaction between man and machine and at the same time we are trying to widen the boundaries of this interaction.
For the moment, humanity as a whole has remained flat-screen pixels and sometimes tactile.
We want to look 5 to 10 years ahead of us and guess the radical changes that will occur with this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox is sold today without Kinect because everyone is interested in control by gesture.
- What does the future hold for us too?
- Although the Kinect has made the interaction physical, a lot of things happen on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
Information capture has been improved (the system is receiving more data), but performance, for the time being, has not really been improved.
We're trying to change this and we're working on truly 3D imaging systems that work on different technologies, including projection technologies.
We have to get the computer world out of ours, into the physical world, make it more tactile.
For this, however, it is necessary to identify not only the user, but also the surrounding space.
In this way, we can complement the real world with virtual objects in a more practical form.
And for starters, let's get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think of voice control?
She's appreciated, but isn't she overestimated?
One cannot say that it is the panacea: the question of confidentiality arises because one does not always want to inform others of his actions or his intentions.
In fact, each type of interaction with the computer is good, but each one in its niche.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project for which we thought of gestures, not broad gestures, but rather discrete, restricted gestures.
The gestures were not captured by the camera, but by a hand-worn bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is currently large, but it is theoretically possible to reduce it to the size of a watch.
In fact, the future will be marked by mixed command, for example: gesture + voice.
- What do you mean?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass you that can?
You would do it with words and gestures.
- Usually, I'm just talking.
- Oh, this is gonna be hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or can't do at some point?
- Not necessarily, but it's a matter of mutual rapprochement.
I think that very soon we will have to work on the development of new types of sensors that will enable us to better identify man's reactions.
These can be laser sensors, they produce fairly good resolution in depth and this is very important.
- If we're interested in your work on Xbox Kinect sensors, what don't you like about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth, or anything else?
- In principle, it is on the current generation that we base our work on 3D recognition.
It would obviously be good to get about 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 c / s.
But the problem is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Compared to this last point, all the current technologies are quite good, this adds work to the algorithms designers.
It is necessary to keep in mind the resolution in X and Y axes, but also in Z.
Speed also matters a lot, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the 30 c / s are really not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche of our Redmond lab gave the sensor touch a steady processing delay of between 1 and 100 µs, with the current sensors closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands how this influences the interaction of man and machine.
I would need a device like this in my work, but I don't need to touch, to get more frames at the second.
- But shouldn't we increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras," one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other, a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually a usual sensor of the visible field.
It is not used to define the depth of the object.
A lot of cameras could solve this problem...
Or make it worse by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be interesting to create a flexible product similar to Kinect, play with the camera curve and see how it could help define locations.
- As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that from the point of view of the daily use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most promising platforms?
- Of course, walking around all the time with a smartphone with your hands raised is not practical but here's what I think: the best option would be a "transient" augmented reality that would allow you from a cloud platform to switch glasses to the smartphone.
Glasses are a very personal device and that's what makes them strong (the personal elements are the only ones you see) and at the same time their weakness: the reality increased from glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects in collaboration with other people.
- Let us imagine for a moment that the handling of virtual holographic objects in the air is no longer accessible only to Tony Stark in Iron Man but also to the mere mortal.
There is a problem that opponents of this idea point their finger at: there is no touch!
Hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my classes, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth could be the addition of tactile sensations.
For the moment, one of the interesting techniques is the use of the second hand to serve as image support.
She's recording the pressure perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really intended to attribute palpability to these "images in the air": for example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed towards a precise point where the finger is located and which gives you the feeling, for the moment still weak, of a breath of air on the ends of the fingers.
There are also the bracelets worn on the wrists that influence nerve endings of the fingers, they are also an axis of work with perspectives.
- And you tried to cheat the brain?
Make him think he feels what he should normally feel when he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried yet.
There is still one task below which it will take a long time to get hurt: how to make someone who is physically in a very small space believe that he is walking in an almost infinite open space - we are working on the concepts of treadmills (nothing to do with those found in fitness clubs), mobile platforms and also giant balls.
For the moment, we can only moderately deceive the brain, there are still many years of work to be done.
This is what makes the work on virtual reality so interesting for the researcher: many things are still in the absolute state of fertilization.
