The head of the ISC (Supreme Audit Institution) said: "the control of pseudo self-employment (in Czech" Švarc system ") has failed because of politicians.
In the field of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and quality legislation, but it is lagging behind in its implementation.
This was stated by Miloslav Kala, Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Institution in an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and, in my opinion, that is what is lacking in us," Kala said in her commentary on the current situation.
A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cited Petr Nečas' approach to the "Švarc system" as an example of abusive practice.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls; is it therefore allowed or prohibited?
"The law must be applied in one way or another, so if it forbids something, even the head of government cannot stop an inspecting authority from demanding compliance with the law," Kala says.
At the meeting of the Monitoring Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you referred to a Czech-German project in which the public procurement laws of these two countries were compared.
What was the specific question?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation and a practice itself.
We have gathered all this together and, although this control procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have emerged: generally speaking, our legislation may be "more stringent and of better quality," but, according to certain parameters, the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not enough to continually develop increasingly detailed rules but that it is necessary to devote ourselves to the very implementation of the law.
How can this project help you in practice and what does it mean for you?
Common control of this kind should help us to stop trying to clarify the laws, to lower and to improve the thresholds, where this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this objective.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by red tape, that those who seek its faults will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems with the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an institution similar to our SAI or a different way of organizing?
As for the institutions, like the ISC, the Bundesrechnungshof operates there, which is organised in a similar way, it also has a council constituted somewhat differently, but these two institutions basically proceed in a similar way.
The powers are also, to a certain extent, similar, however with a degree of similarity to our system: since Germany is a federal structure, it also has similar rates of account at the level of the various Länder.
The HRB can only control federal money, which in our case is the same as the state's resources.
The public funds managed at home by the regions and municipalities are controlled there at the level of the Länder 'accounts.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas, Germany is often referred to as a model, but one cannot say that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better detectives?
No, probably not, but I repeat, I don't have any comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we regard as a model, also faces a whole series of problems.
Otherwise they wouldn't have any advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has been meant for you, as an institution, by the amendment of the law on public procurement, are its effects already being felt?
As this amendment has come into force relatively recently, it does not yet have an impact on our monitoring operations.
Since we are carrying out ex post checks, there is a certain delay.
Our observations relate only to the process of preparing future checks at the moment - we have launched a new "risk detection tool" with which we have screened almost 14,000 public contracts - where these changes will of course be felt, because the thresholds have been changed as well as the conditions for certain types of tender procedures and so on.
Do you therefore consider the adoption of this law to be rather an advantage or an additional burden for the administration?
I believe that this law is a step in the right direction and I hope that the future will confirm it.
The problem that can arise is that these rules become more stringent and that they cannot be respected.
Already under the previous rules, the provider (e.g. the regional council, in the case of regional operational programmes) forced the subject to accept that any breach of the law on markets means a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it really useful to make the law stricter in this way?
No, not that way, I think.
The system must exclude those who want to attack the system or abuse it, but not punish those who make formal errors without affecting the decision-making process.
Such a system will put more pressure on the administration.
So what's the solution to get out of this?
Let's look where we're not going.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with so-called Švarc system controls - what does that mean?
