In May, we will play for the first time in the spring of Prague; here too, we will surely prepare a quality programme with interesting guests.
We would also like to play next year at the Czech Republic's house in New York and personally, once in the United States, I would like to combine concerts in Washington and Chicago.
Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played for example in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the organization and logistics of your tours?
It's not as bad as it sounds at first.
We have five members in an electric chair whose gear must travel in a hold, of course we also carry a lot of luggage and instruments boxes....
So far everything has gone more or less well, ČSA and British Airways were always perfectly prepared for us, they surprised me more than once.
Even in Moscow, where we returned recently, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to your travel abroad, you can compare how these countries differ in terms of access facilities for people with reduced mobility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities, and so on.
What have been your experiences so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than at home, we have just witnessed in Moscow that in the east all is still in an initial phase.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is still very little accessible to people with disabilities; there it is not yet common for a person to move alone in an electric chair in the centre of the city.
They do not yet consider it obvious to give priority to a person in a wheelchair in an elevator.
Fortunately, there too, an association is being set up to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
How do we still have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're still late for...
It is important to mention that improvements and improvements always depend on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to travel alone in public spaces; they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
It is still not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities are actively involved in social life, on this point, you, The Tap Tap, are rather at the forefront of progress!
Public respect and access is one thing, but the situation will really start to change when we have famous athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers.
For the moment, they are only isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, let's go back a few years, what prompted you in 1998 to create this group?
I started working as an educator at the Jedlička Institute, where I found myself surrounded by many young people willing to invest in something.
And since I myself am a musician (I play, among other things, the saxophone), with a colleague, we have created a music activity.
And then, over time, as our moderator Láā a Angelovič says, we lost a little control of the situation (laughs).
Success has only happened in the last few years, if I'm not mistaken?
It's true, building relationships with known singers and actively working to promote the group has helped us.
