Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the Agency, the second member of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to space started much earlier.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. Šternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, at which he presented ideas from his avant-garde book "Introduction to Astronautics."
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his work "Introduction to Astronautics."
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of world-renowned astronautics, his contribution was rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the hidden side of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a driveway was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the draisin.
The only known information about this raisin is from the press of the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is apparent from the records that this research has reached the trial stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, research has stopped.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were aimed at the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects using rocket technology were carried out by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of Problem, which contains four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a company dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to join the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951), and by the autumn PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first President of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the Rakieta Meteorologiczna (RM) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This 1800-metre-wide rocket was 80 cm long and weighed just under 5 kg.
An improved version, RM-1A, was subsequently built and, in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were initiated in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 metres long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, succeeded the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed and distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B the volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C was 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were later built.
Mention should also be made of Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of the programme.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision gave rise to considerable public discussion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Liberalism-oriented economic systems, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means, in practical terms, that the various economic entities and national economic systems are in constant conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour prices (wages) create pressure on prices.
This means that a producer is trying by importing goods sold at low prices to resist economic competition by 'making the competitor's price more expensive', with the aim of removing a larger share of the market and thus increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, buying at low prices or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no responsibility from the social point of view and thus from the point of view of responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the State's social security contributions necessarily increase.
All this situation intensifies the perfect bad will of the entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage caused to the whole of society by this race for profit.
This situation is so widely known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create a situation in the various economies in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own populations in order to attract foreign capital.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking social collapse into account.
This is reflected mainly in the amendments to existing laws.
The aim is to force its own population economically to accept the diktat of private capital prices, particularly in the field of wages.
This occurs, on the one hand, by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, by the restriction of employees' rights in the field of labour legislation.
This leads to increasing poverty and deepening the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, there have been public food distribution points for years for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own work.
The number of such persons is already counted in millions.
In the context of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the State is obliged to pay a supplement so that they reach the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal has been brought to light, for example, in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of almost all the southern EU Member States undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century) or to live with destitute wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital invested in their country.
The question here is: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will pass from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to Latin America as a whole.
Liberal theory and the media claim, to get tired of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the controlled economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and, even today, does not, according to its own selfish interests, govern politics and, by the same token, the entire State.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is an almost all-powerful lobby present in all States.
This results in a desperate situation in the area of corruption, in the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is reprehensible but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that because of the lack of financial resources, national ministries delegate the development of draft laws to law firms closely linked to industry.
These bills are then adopted by the Bundestag.
The entire power comes not from the people, as Western constitutions say, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberalism-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire at the time of Caesar and Pompey": "The State was long in collapse and the functions were attributed by violence.
Bribes, favors obtained illegally, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The underside and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with voices already sold... "..." Honest people did not seek any functions, it resulted once the state remained without consuls for 8 months... "'It really began to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man..." It was true that Appianos had in mind Pompey, but it was Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into an absolute regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer able to understand and assert the interests of society as a whole.
This results, as in the past, in an unprecedented decline of elites, without any effort to carry out far-reaching reforms.
We must therefore seek the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
As things stand, the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that today's elites completely ignore the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future human casualties, the humanitarian and social crises we witness today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both at international and internal European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms that will strengthen the investment of State capital in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
