The film Argo: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of demonstrators composed of Islamist students stormed the American embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to liberate the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that gave America a small victory.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated adventures, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran thanks to a rocambolesque cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to make sightings for the shooting of a science-fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan of exfiltration expert Tony Mendez called for Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were held and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained for a long time secret, the film being based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is, on the one hand, a politically conceived thriller, but also a "caper movie," the story of a successful blow, of a treachery - such as, for example, in the Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
The atmospheres follow each other: documentary-style Teheran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the epoch of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been transcribed in the film, there are no great differences),
lighter passages of Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting stopped arousing ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark cop "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also the first film by Affleck that does not take place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity, which also suggests confusion and unpredictability when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect in fictitious scenes (the false shooting team in Tehran's bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to confine himself to a subject that actually offered few exciting scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
He does very well, he sometimes adds some elements to the reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the airstrip is quite drawn by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have earned a bigger place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, it is seen with a moderate interest, appreciating the retro style and realization of the 70s.
He trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a history still, in a way, unfinished to date, and as an illustration of the exaggeration of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the business.
