The architects of the firm MVRVV prove that true adventures are not just about imagination. To convince yourself, just contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is fun, it is very futuristic, at last something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist in a large nearby company, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes voluntarily to one of those dorky libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, has a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back a few neurons to the brains, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty little miniatures of painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive has remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realized that there was only one way to regain control of statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from the architectural office of Rotterdam MVRDV, master of daring stick diagrams and creator of often cynical and witty buildings, accepted the project with its usual phlegm and competed in 2003 with five books under his arm and a chuckle on his face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, disconcerting and shrugging their shoulders, Maas, the unbridled, encroached on his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and ended his speech, supported by activist arguments, with one: "dear common!"
Here it is, my proposal for the Spijkenisse Mountain of Books, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain was thrown out of the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012."
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this dull little town, which until now had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian area and a town hall of staggering ugliness, whose white facades invite to think that they are home to a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado from the book under a cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the true joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you cross the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the floor made of Dutch bricks and elegant verbales speak unequivocally the language of municipal public places.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking at public benches, dogs, and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and books.
"Normally, the library shelves are located along the façade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," explains Willy Maas.
We completely disrupted the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from inside to outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skilfully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the centre for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panelling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes stair ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project leader at the town of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
So one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
In the Netherlands, one millimetre thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, and can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates of a thickness of four centimetres.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes colour and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us an amazing view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and jars.
The latter create an atmosphere, but above all they contribute to maintaining the ideal level of moisture in the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the new soul
"It's amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model ecological project," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is controlled by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on days of good weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across from the glass façade serve as a sun shield, intercepting much of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The completely automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already here.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "finally recovered soul."
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This has made it possible to fill the gaps in the library, which has not yet been completely filled (today, it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration. "
In this way, MVRDV has achieved the master discipline which is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity."
Spijkenisse wrote a new literary history page.
Even if she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the creation of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose abstention in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a difficult political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but it did not want to be too critical of Israel.
At the March 2011 Libyan uprising, Germany had also chosen abstention in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO imposed this measure.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is in the process of reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy, so to speak, defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore faced several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that they are still trying to find this role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows the will to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position vis-à-vis the Middle East conflict and abstention in the UN vote?
Germany first has important markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to hit public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to this, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I believe that the Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I believe that the fracture is not so serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do the views differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly demonstrating a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think that makes it easy for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore form part of a wider political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are doing now on the issue of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will play a role as a locomotive in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been a delicate one.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they must play a role that is more important to their independence.
Is Germany playing a leading role on the international stage, and does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does it still have difficulty in taking on leadership roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulties in playing a more important role.
Looking, for example, at the euro crisis, we see that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German sentiments are heard.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to deal with very diverse neighbours and opinions, and that is not easy.
Today the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this void, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
