Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common STIs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Pubic lice and scabies belong to parasitic STIs.
Which groups are primarily concerned?
Syphilis and gonorrhea often occur in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is responsible for at least four out of five reported cases of syphilis in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, infections related to chlamydia, trichomonase, candidiasis (fungal), blennorrhagia and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV transmission between heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed within this group.
Among young people, there is a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections than among other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections concern young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the trend in the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis has more than doubled in 10 years, from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been decreasing.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth over the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, urinary pain, white loss, pain in the lower stomach, and the appearance of buttons and warts.
However, they do not cause any regular pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How can we protect ourselves?
Condoms may reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect 100%.
This is because sexually transmitted disease pathogens can also be transmitted through lubricating infection or close body contact.
The experts therefore recommend that any person who frequently changes sexual partners should take regular examinations.
Most of the rapidly detected STIs can be cured and delayed sequelae can be avoided.
