Norway's rakfisk: is it the most fragrant fish in the world?
Norway's five million people enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret of the success of the country be linked to the appetite of the locals for an extremely fragrant fish?
Take some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet, dirty soccer clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway's most popular dishes.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this smell, omnipresent, permeates the air.
The rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a duration - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can go up to a year.
When the darkness settles and it is cold, the Norwegian gather in mass to attend a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to this incredible culinary speciality.
"You eat raw, then swallow a glass of aquavit," explains Havard Halvarsen, a local full-time firefighter who is also called "Rakfisk General," responsible for managing the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of drink.
"Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk," says Havard.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid passing it under your nose, it's not bad - it makes you think of a sushi who would have spent long hours on a bus.
The rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was submerged in air-tight water barrels and then salted in the fall.
Then, during the winter, once well fermented, the fish went out and - undoubtedly with the senses weakened by alcohol - ate.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegian people were forced to leave their country to find work, emigrating mainly to the United States.
The population is now growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health care system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so much richer than Norway, cross the border to work.
The rakfisk is considered to be something important, a vital, though fragrant, element of Norway's past.
It's one of the most expensive dishes.
