Since the early 1970s, Norway has owed its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
"But oil is not the only reason for our success," explains Anna, our waitress, with blonde hair and in the eyes of a piercing blue, the image of Nordic well-being, with a platter of rakfisk in her hand.
We are - how do you say - prudent people.
His English, like that of most people who live here, is perfect.
We're discreet, we don't like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - everything, with the exception of a small percentage of money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for future generations.
