Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, say prosecutors.
The prosecutors are trying to counter the claims of ill-treatment that Bradley Manning was allegedly subjected to during the detention.
The trial concerns Manning's detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning's kidnapping took place under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors attempted to demonstrate on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being responsible for the biggest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. Army -- missed numerous opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
During cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein stated that recordings of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not reveal any complaints regarding his treatment.
Cross-examination -- at a hearing, the defence filed a motion requiring Manning to be closed on the ground that the kidnapping took place in very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified that he wanted to commit suicide during his detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while serving in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein discussed with Manning the forms that the officers had completed after meeting Manning during his detention in Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he received from his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received in the prison was generally "very professional."
The forms do not mention any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, said Fein.
Manning replied that he had expressed concerns about certain problems orally and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the problems raised.
"They wrote" no problem "(after addressing the concerns), but that did not mean that I had not raised any problems," Manning said.
Military judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention at the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed to indicate a "risk of injury."
The military stated that they had assigned this restrictive status to him -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was fine, and I wanted to be removed from my status... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view," said Manning.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he had considered suicide while in Kuwait and had fainted once because of the heat.
He added that the fact that he had not been kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon at this cage," said Manning on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning stated that he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also added that the only items at his disposal were a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay in motion because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also said that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards didn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so that they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint about Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with cover during the appeal.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning stated that he had inferred from his custody's order that he had to drop his cover that might have hidden his nudity, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to release it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before, as he allegedly tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or flip-flops to hurt himself, but that he had not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, his flip-flops, and his glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he is found guilty before a court martial, a trial that is expected to take place early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning is considering pleading guilty to the least serious crimes and fighting for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing should resume this weekend, with prosecutors who should argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
Charges brought against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in illegal publication of information on the Internet, and transmission of information related to national defence.
If all charges are upheld, he is liable to life imprisonment.
