For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn a living carrying the sulfur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of Indonesia's island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphuric gas from the earth's entrails solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulfur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets, which he loads on his shoulders through steep trails.
There are only 250 metres to the top of the volcano, which peaks at 2,386 metres, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb that distance, at a turtle's pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents euro for every kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once on the top, he makes a road between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and carrying the heavy baskets painfully, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company has installed a little below at 1.850 meters altitude.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry at Rs 10,000 (83 euro cents) since it is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"As we transport about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) every trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes 3 hours and he ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what it would earn in the fields.
"The income of miners is very high here, where coffee is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)," says the bearer who used to work as a mason on Bali's tourist island.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and her eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
