The Unasur Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration having been made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven representatives present.
Efe tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially indicated that it would be disclosed after the summit had closed, and then stated that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian Government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulated among journalists was that given by press officers of some of the governments of Unasur who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were demanding more important information.
Later, Peru's presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South America-Arab Countries Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was requested by the press, it had also not disseminated the declaration also known as the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to set up safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the availability of information to the maximum extent possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that determines a different border between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and declared that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the arguments of both parties in the trial that Lima brought against Santiago, which begins on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing before this international court today," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country respectful of international law, of the peaceful resolution of international disputes, treaties and tribunals," added President Piñera, giving President Humala a handshake alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two Presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia had denounced the Bogota Pact this week, by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on maritime limits with Nicaragua which it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from the Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was instructed to open the deliberations in the morning and close the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The Representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the action lines of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits."
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our people," concluded President Humala.
"We have decided to favour a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic channels," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were located on the transversal axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed for a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme discussed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, stated, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to discuss the maritime dispute calmly through a ruling of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We are going to revise all these avenues, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua, which will ask for a discussion with that country," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we are going to settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," added President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they have planned to witness the takeover of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, at the summit, the Defence Ministers of the bloc will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of the Unasur, although the latter is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
