He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 1990s, where there was a lot of doubt, little choice of treatment and more stigma.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless."
At that time, having AIDS meant death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said HCG's head of the HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, and he takes as his reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
The infectiologist and HIV / AIDS expert, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a fatal disease, but that the number of years of survival and the quality of life depend on the level of immune system assignment that patients had at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years for CD4 levels of 200 and up to 50 years for those who reach 500 CD4 levels.
Simply put, this means that for someone who receives a positive HIV diagnosis at age 25, "as long as he or she remains under control, he or she will be able to live without problems until he or she is 75 years old," the scientist interviewed explained.
In order to put this progress into context, it is necessary to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
While it is true that mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of AIDS-related deaths increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60 per cent of the patients registered on the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths until May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
Then why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the past 12 years at least, we have never lacked medication, the problem is that patients are reaching very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact: "nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what is needed to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to carry out earlier diagnoses and, in order to do so, to offer massive screening tests to all those who request it."
The specialists and members of the State AIDS Prevention Council of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do his testing in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and, despite his young age, he was already carrying AIDS and suffering from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer tumour that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know.
"If I'm going to die, I better have fun three times a week," they say, "I'm not.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To date, his parents only know that he suffers from cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march of World AIDS Day.
Let them test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better, and if they already have the diagnosis, they must know that we can live like everyone else, by being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
