The insurance action will demand non-prosperity and require a review of the trial by a higher court, in this case the United States Supreme Court of Justice.
The most serious thing is that the court ignored a document sent by the Mexican government on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the court") in which Vitro's procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act was detailed, pointing out that it freed him from the conventions signed by the two countries to bring it up to the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he pointed out that the country had complied with the United Nations Commission on International Trade, namely the rules for cross-border insolvency, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
