Héctor "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
The globe-trotter of basketball "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, travelled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as great as that of Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a brain hemorrhage condemned him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, national basketball team player, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I have worn several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, like when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalls during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life."
Reyes doesn't exaggerate when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and souvenirs that remind him of his unusual itinerary, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loved most were those who reminded him of his time as a player on the Vaqueros team in the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as co-manager or manager of the team.
"It was my best years, the ones I took the most advantage of because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
It's been a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired to the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead, "says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me, "I have a strong player for you, he's two meters tall.
Do you want it? "
That's how to start Mincy, one of Puerto Rico's best players.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and one of the best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He was delighted with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great champion of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy's charges on the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we came fourth and should have won the bronze medal if that Canadian judge hadn't played us the last game, said Reyes.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as was the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and beat the United States team, which was quite similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 because of a knee problem.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the players suspended by the imbroglio of the Pan American Games of Mar del Plata, we have won gold against all prognosis.
What was Puerto Rico's best player?
Without a doubt, this is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics at international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico dominated at this level as did Piculín.
And that without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues he played for.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest success in the federation?
Being part of the most glorious time of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What do you have to do?
There are things I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalization of minor categories.
For example, the Ponce boys play only in their area and compete only with teams from other parts of the island during national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when this is not necessarily necessary.
At least I saw the advantage of mandatory certifications and courses for managers, field staff and arbitrators.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, watch music from my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally watch basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide by the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas," in which he represented an unscrupulous, formidable and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday night of complications of cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for the Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved most again," the family said.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on that Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who was interpreting his wife's role in the original series and in the rest, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said his press secretary, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I'm going to miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he was living his life," Gray said in a press release.
The doctors had diagnosed liver cirrhosis in Larry Hagman in 1992 and he admitted to drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was found to have a malignant liver tumor and had a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas," Hagman had made himself known on television as an ordinary guy in the series "Jinny of My Dreams" broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he interpreted the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an attractive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He has also played in two comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his movie roles are well received by critics in "The Group," "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors."
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the deliciously disgraceful J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their relatives was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?," invented to maintain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, has generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
As a result, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the response was revealed in an episode in November 1980, an average of 41 million viewers were in front of their screens and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had brought together 50 million viewers.
It was J.R. 's sister-in-law, Kristin (performed by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had made her pregnant and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played Ewing's role as a corrupted and insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband trying to put his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen in prison (Linda Gray).
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "This is the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-protagonist of the original series, remembered this Friday of Hagman as a man "immense, both on the small screen and in life."
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of all of us, who have had the chance to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes has already been completed for the second season and a sixth is in the process of being realized, informed the channel.
For the time being, neither Warner nor TNT have communicated how Hagman's death will be included in the series.
Originally from Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who enjoyed fame with classical works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan."
Mary Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to her in 1931 when she was married to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He took his first steps on the scenes of New York theatres in the early 1950s and served in the air force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
It was there that he met the young Swedish interior decorator Maj Axelsson and married him.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for many years in the California city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoirs "Hello Darlin ': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life" (in French: Hello Darlin': Les mémoires merritoyables de J.R)
"I didn't write anything in this book that could hurt anyone or affect them in any way," he told the press at that time.
After his liver transplant, he became an active organ donation activist and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist worried patients.
"I advise them, I trust them again, I come with them when they come for surgery and then," he says in 1996.
I'm trying to offer them some comfort, like, "Don't be afraid, it won't be easy for a little while, but it'll be fine."
He has also been a tobacco activist and has participated in several campaigns.
A course on the "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the religion teacher Stuart Charme decided to give a lecture on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hook there: the end of the "big count" of the Maya calendar, on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charme had no idea what was expected of him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax abyss that some have dubbed "the Armageddon of Debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end of time thought the apocalypse would be triggered.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," Professor Charme told his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey) this week.
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and told it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is evil is good for those who believe in apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher to lecture on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and explore how they can be compared with real-life examples.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible," said Vacker.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World."
"We add" 2012 "to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world does not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster," students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed the day before the Apocalypse, which does not leave students of any choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"It was completed in two hours," said Restall about his course for high-level students, composed of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
The students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
